LTV forecast with classification models¶

Background¶

Flaw in identifying profitable customers

Marketers commonly estimate customer lifetime value in order to decide which customers are worth continued investment. In the previous project, I identified the best customers using RFM analysis based on historical data. However, I might have overlooked the real option of abandoning unprofitable customer since what I had been using was past figures. That is, the customers that you decided not bother aquiring might be actually profitable in the future.

Find the customers who are valuable in the future

We might want to identify the future profitable segment for a set of customers using the RFM approach and machine learning models. This helps us pinpoint the potential profitable customers so we could direct marketing dollars to the right customers.

Objective¶

To identify the most profitable customer segment in the future among existing customers who have a known transaction history

Approach¶

LTV = revenue - cost^

  1. Period: Define a timeframe for LTV calculation -> Lets say 1 year as the timeframe

Since I have 2 years of data available, I will set the middle point as threshold date:

  • Orders before the threshold date: used to train the model (for preparing the feature set)
  • Orders after the threshold date: used to compute the target value (LTV cluster)
  1. Feature set: Compute the RFM scores for each customer and use the scores as the feature set
  2. LTV prediction: Use multiclass classfication models to predict 1-year LTV segment for each customer and find the most profitable segment

Group into 3 LTV segment: 0 - least profitable, 3 - most profitable

^Remark: there is no cost value in the given dataset, assuming cost=0 in this notebook.

Steps¶

  1. Load & clean the data

  2. Split the dataframe with threshold date into 2 partitions (1st year & 2nd year)

  3. Prepare feature set by computing RFM scores using K-means Clustering (1st year data)

  • Recency: number of days since most recent purchase date
  • Frequency: number of transactions within the period
  • Monetary: total sales attributed to the customer
  1. Data preprocessing
  2. Build classification models and evaluate model performance
  3. Hyperparamenter tuning to improve model performance
  4. Conclusion

============================================================================

About the dataset¶

This Online Retail II data set contains all the transactions occurring for a UK-based and registered, non-store online retail between 01/12/2009 and 09/12/2011.The company mainly sells unique all-occasion gift-ware. Many customers of the company are wholesalers.

Column Descriptors¶

  • InvoiceNo: Invoice number. Nominal. A 6-digit integral number uniquely assigned to each transaction. If this code starts with - the letter 'c', it indicates a cancellation.
  • StockCode: Product (item) code. Nominal. A 5-digit integral number uniquely assigned to each distinct product.
  • Description: Product (item) name. Nominal.
  • Quantity: The quantities of each product (item) per transaction. Numeric.
  • InvoiceDate: Invice date and time. Numeric. The day and time when a transaction was generated.
  • UnitPrice: Unit price. Numeric. Product price per unit in sterling (Â£).
  • CustomerID: Customer number. Nominal. A 5-digit integral number uniquely assigned to each customer.
  • Country: Country name. Nominal. The name of the country where a customer resides.

Data Source: https://www.kaggle.com/mathchi/online-retail-ii-data-set-from-ml-repository

2. Split the dataframe¶

The dataset consists of 2 years of transaction data from 2009-12-01 to 2011-12-09. I will take 1 year of data, calculate RFM and use it for predicting next year.

  • Threshold date: 2010-12-01
  • 1st data set: 2009-12-01 to 2010-11-30 (feature set to train the models)
  • 2nd data set: 2010-12-01 to 2011-11-30 (containing target values)

df_1styear = df[(df.InvoiceDate > '2009-12-01')&(df.InvoiceDate < '2010-11-30')]
df_2ndyear = df[(df.InvoiceDate > '2010-12-01')&(df.InvoiceDate < '2011-11-30')]

3. Compute RFM scores using K-means Clustering as feature set¶

Caculate the RFM values

Based on the 1st year dataset(df_1styear), I will set the most recent date in the dataset as the observation point to caculate the recency.

  • Recency = observation point - most recent transaction date
  • Frequency = #invoice counts within the period
  • Monetary = Sum of transaction value for each customer (transaction value = Quantity * Price)
In [27]:
#Create the dataframe with unique customer ID and the most recent date for each customer
df_user = df_1styear.groupby('Customer ID')['InvoiceDate'].max().reset_index()
df_user.columns=['CustomerID','MostRecentInvoiceDate']

# Calculate the recency for each customer 
# Recency = observation point - transaction date
df_user['Recency'] = df_1styear['InvoiceDate'].max() - df_user.MostRecentInvoiceDate

#convert Recency to integer format
df_user['Recency'] = pd.to_timedelta(df_user.Recency, errors='coerce').dt.days

#drop the 'most recent date' column
df_user.drop('MostRecentInvoiceDate',axis=1,inplace=True)

#Create the dataframe with unique customer ID and the frquency for each customer
df_freq = df_1styear.groupby('Customer ID')['InvoiceDate'].count().reset_index()
df_freq.columns=['CustomerID','Frequency']

#Calculate the total transaction amount for each customer and store the value in new column
df_1styear['TotalAmount'] = df_1styear.Quantity*df_1styear.Price

#Create the dataframe with unique customer ID and the total transaction amount for each customer
df_money = df_1styear.groupby('Customer ID')['TotalAmount'].sum().reset_index()
df_money.columns=['CustomerID','Monetary']

#Merge the tables to create a single table containing RFM columns
df_user = df_user.merge(df_freq,on='CustomerID')
df_user = df_user.merge(df_money,on='CustomerID')

Compute the RFM scores with K-means clustering

The higher scores should indicate better values, i.e. lower recency value should have higher Recency score; higher frequency value should have higher frequency score; higher monetary value should have higher monetary score.

From previous project, the optimal #clusters was 4 which would be set as the parameter for K-means clustering, i.e. scoring will be 0 to 3.

In [30]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
In [31]:
#K-means clustering, using n_clusters = 4 which is the optimal value determinded in previous RFM project.
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4,init='k-means++')

#Create cluster column with respect to RFM value
df_user['RecencyCluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(df_user[['Recency']])
df_user['FrequencyCluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(df_user[['Frequency']])
df_user['MonetaryCluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(df_user[['Monetary']])

#function to reorder the cluster number so that higher score indicates better value
def cluster_reorder(df,cluster_field,RFM_value_field,ascending_boolean):
    df_order = df.groupby(cluster_field)[RFM_value_field].mean().sort_values(ascending=ascending_boolean).reset_index()
    df_order['new_cluster'] = df_order.index
    df_order.drop(RFM_value_field,axis=1,inplace=True)

    df = df.merge(df_order,how='left',on=cluster_field)

    df.drop(cluster_field,axis=1,inplace=True)
    df.rename(columns={'new_cluster':cluster_field},inplace=True)
    return df

#Apply the re-order function to RFM clusters
df_user = cluster_reorder(df_user,'RecencyCluster','Recency',False)
df_user = cluster_reorder(df_user,'FrequencyCluster','Frequency',True)
df_user = cluster_reorder(df_user,'MonetaryCluster','Monetary',True)

5. Build classification models¶

Models selected

Will apply 3 classifiers and go for the one with best performance:

A. Support Vector Machine
B. Random Forest
C. XGBClassifier

Precision vs Recall in evalutation

Precision = TP/(TP+FP)

Precision trys to answer: what proportion of positive identifications was actually correct? If precision of the model is 50% for cluster 2, when the model predicts the customer is in high LTV segment, it is correct 50% of the time.

Recall = TP/(TP+FN)

Recall trys to answer: what proportion of actual positives was identified correctly? If recall is 50% for cluster 2, then the model correctly identifies 50% of high LTV customers.

I will use Recall to evaluate the model performance, as it gives a measure of how accurately the model is able to identify the actual high LTV customers.

Stratified k-fold Cross Validation

The default Cross Validation method being used here, which divides a limited dataset into k folds and enforces the class distribution in each split of the data to match the distribution in the complete training datset.

In [54]:
#set up model variables
rf = RandomForestClassifier()
xgb = XGBClassifier()
svc = SVC()

#list to store model name and recall values
model_name = []
recall = []

#cross validate each model and output the mean recall value for each model (set #splits for kfold = 5)
for model in (rf,xgb,svc):
    
    model_name.append(model.__class__.__name__)

#compute the macro average of recall values across 3 classes as we valued the minority class (LTV cluster 2) the most
#get mean of recall values among 5 folds of data
    recall.append(cross_validate(model,X,y,cv=5,scoring='recall_macro')['test_score'].mean())

#comparison table to show model vs their mean recall value
pd.DataFrame({'model':model_name,'Recall':recall})
